description.text:
After getting a Spacemouse wireless, I realized that it did not come with any way to safely transport the mouse or USB receiver other than the original packaging.  So, I designed one to be 3D printed.  
Right now I have it designed to accept a 3mm pin of some kind for the hinge (I'm using a piece of wire hanger).  
I've printed this out, and it works, but there are a few things that could function better.  I'm working on a revision that tightens up the hinges and will include "keys" on the lid to help things line up a little more solid.  I'll be revising this model and uploading the update.  It likely will not include the text on the lid as pulling the support material that printed in the letters is pain to remove.  Once this is reprinted, I will likely use XTC 3Dd or acetone vapor to create a better finish.  
I've included the stl files as well as the sketchup files, so feel free to remix and post this as you wish.  I'm still pretty new to 3D modeling and this is probably the most complex thing I've made to date, so I suspect someone here could improve on the design.  Go for it!

description.text:
My wife wanted a spice rack to mount on the inside of a cabinet door. So I designed and printed this off for her. It's a spice rack that is useable on a kitchen counter or in a cabinet, can be hung up too. I made it using Blender and I've included the .blend file along with the .stl file. Cheers! Here is a link to a video of the print:
http://youtu.be/u3h0ZbJy1Mg

I printed the spice rack in PLA with 25% infill on my Ultimaker 2.  It just fit the maximum dimensions for the width of the Ultimaker 2.  If you are going to print a copy with an Ultimaker 2 then use Cura to slice it and try to move it to the left as much as possible, otherwise the Hot-End might bang the right side of your Ultimaker 2 while it is printing.  
Also the front left and right sides have some thin long sides and while printing I added a little tape to add some strength to them until the tops of them reconnected.  You can see the black tape in part of the youtube video.

After cutting my thumb a few times i've been aiming to try my luck on drawing up files to make a thumb protector. This is my rendition of a thumb anvil, THIMBLE! Works great and can't believe i got the angles about right. Angles just are't my thing!  
The little clips printed remarkable, them being so small. The trick is SLOW PRINTING!  I used 20mm/s and 30mm/s on the anvil with 15 second minimum layer time. Printed both clips and anvil at the same time with Simplify3D. Used different speed for each. Print the clips with something else or as i did and they should do fine printed slow.  It only slowed down for the very last few layers of the round top part. .I used .3 layer, as you can see in picture i have some wobble problems, yet it gets me by.  
I'm sure there are thousands of ways to hold the rubber band on, but wanted simple print with no support, rubber band want come off and a quick CAD drawing. Anyone find a better way with these standards please share.   
I was lucky on the rubber band, its just a small one and a tiny bit looser than in want, but will do the job. You may need to search around for a rubber band, i found mine in an assortment i bought a few years ago.  
Hope someone finds use of this, i know i will, use my pocket knife daily and nearly the same time line on pricking my thumb.  
Thanks, Rick.

I crashed my XciteRC Rocket 65XS QC and had some working parts left. I found them a bit to good to throw away so I bought some bigger motors as they are used by Hubsan and made a new chassis. I think it got simple but nice.
The motors clamp in the holes the other parts are attached with rubber bands. The wiring goes through the arms.
The copter you see on the pictures is an older version, I printed it in ABS and had some warping but regardless this thing flies very well. I would recommend to use PLA instead. In the new version I reduced the material and added some pins so it is more easy to attach the rubber bands. In my case the circuit board has some lights so the whole thing glows very nice with the white material.

This is a mount for mounting a AccuRemote 0-16" Electronic Digital Indicator Gauge on an Airwolf HD2x. http://www.amazon.com/dp/B0071SKHAW/ref=wl_it_dp_o_pC_S_ttl?_encoding=UTF8&colid=JNX19TKHE7P3&coliid=IUIQDXO5JX2QN This cheap little gauge lets you really level your print bed with precision. I also use a feeler gauge between the nozzle and the bed instead of a piece of paper and adjust at the back, left corner (where the limit switch is) until I can still feel the nozzle but the indicator reading doesn't change at all when the feeler is slid in and out. The feeler you chose should be an integer multiple of your z axis step (0.02mm). Once you have this set, press the relative button and go to the other 3 corners and adjust until these are zero. Then adjust your z-offset in your slicer software down by the thickness of the feeler gauge used. If this is done correctly, you should not have to adjust the z offset at all when a print starts. It should be perfect. The mount replaces the top hat on the extruder that hold in the filament line feeds. The indicator gauge attaches with the pin. I used the 3" extension piece that comes with the indicator. Remove the indicator while printing. Enjoy. UPDATE: I just added a modified version for the single extruder HD/HDx. See mount2_HD.stl for this version. I included the Solidworks file and an IGS file.

description.text:
Her name is Robotica.
I do not know if my profession is to design, paint or modeling. But Robotica has a little bit of everything. Robotica is an articulated doll. The pieces are joined by elastic cords is all it takes to build once you have printed the pieces. (She wears the same system to steady my little robot http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:555242 )
You can see here as the doll is assembled: http://youtu.be/jnswThHyEy0 More of my artistic works here: http://www.soniaverdu.es/

Is time for giving and sharing, so ...
I have shared this doll without rights to market, but if you are interested in selling it, you can write me, I will give you the authorization to do so you only have to donate 10% of sales price to a charity. I help this foundation http://www.hopesanddreams.org/ , http://www.africadirecto.org or http://quissos.org but you can choose whether you prefer to help with that 10% to other foundations of your country or another in which you have confidence. That is my condition.
If you do not want to sell her I hope you enjoy it !!!

You can choose a head with eyes to print, or eyeless head (this can paint easily and move your eyes, you can hold them with some kind of clay)
I recommend printing oh highest quality for good fitment. No need material support should be needed. The elastic cord that best fits the figurine is 3mm in diameter. Layer height(mm): 0.1
botton/top, Shell thickness(mm): 1.2 It is important for delicate parts of the hands and legs
Fill density%: 15
Print speed(mm/s): 40
Interior Support : none . But brim is important as there are only some little spots touching the buildplate, in all except the feet piezs.
I've printed pla 210º (c)

comments.text:
I've noticed that many of the left-side parts are 'inside out', i.e. the surface normals point inwards. This doesn't apply to the little support pyramids, but only to the shape itself. So if you load into meshlab, for instance, these areas are black instead of gray (black is used for the 'back' of a mesh).
If a left side part is created from a right side part by mirroring all the coordinates, without re-ordering the vertices on each triangle, this is what will happen - the vertices in each triangle are supposed to be in CCW order as seen from the outside, so simply mirroring the coordinates also has the effect of turning the part inside out. Many slicing tools won't care, but others could get confused. In particular, the 'inside' sphere cutting a space away in the 'mano' part would become an outside sphere, and might be seen by some tools as the 'proper' part.
Also, it seems that both hands (the portion with just the fingers and palm) are inside out. You can manually invert normals in Meshlab; also, putting the parts through netfabb should fix all of this automatically; but Cura doesn't get confused by inverted meshes, I didn't need to do anything to handle these issues.

description.text:
Not strictly a derivative, but serves a similar purpose.
I need a thing that can hold onto a bushing on one side, and perpendicular to that, can hold onto a rod of a specified size.
The default sizes for this thing is 5/16" on one side, and 11mm on the other.  The bushing I am using has an inner diameter of 1/4", and outer diameter of 5/16".  On the perpendicular, I'm inserting a carbon fiber rod that has an outer diameter of roughly 11mm.  That rod can be friction fit, or glued, or whatever, depending on what you're doing.

1) Figure out where you might be able to use a perpendicular fitting for round rods.
2) Print one of these out
3) Slip a bushing into the side that goes all the way through
4) Slip a matching smooth steel rod into the bushing to form an axle
5) Slip your stationary rod in the perpendicular hole
6) Rejoice!

description.text:
Update (4 Oct 2017)
The "Swap_Catches" option now affects which piece is considered the vertical piece for the "Dual_Vertical" option. This can be useful for those who need to mount the holder horizontally, and at the same time avoid blocking the charging port. Older versions are available as a zip files.

Update (31 Jul 2017)
Added a "Swap_Catches" option. When set to true, this swaps the catches on the vertical and horizontal piece. The vertical piece will have the "hook" catch, while the horizontal piece will have the straight catch. This is useful if you need to mount the holder on a horizontal bar, or if you wish to mount your phone horizontally. If you want the original version, both v1 and v2 are available as a zip files.

Update (11 Jul 2016)
Added a "Dual_Vertical" option. When set to true, this allows you to attach two vertical pieces instead of one. This can be useful if you want to charge your phone while it's in the holder. Added a "Grip" option. This allows you to increase/reduce the height of the top catch, trading off grip tightness to ease of insertion. Few other minor changes. If you want the original version, it's available as a zip file.

Update (22 May 2016)
Added a vertical offset option when using the Customizer. The original design always places the side grip right at the middle, and this can obstruct or press on the side buttons for some phones. The vertical offset option solves this problem by shifting the phone up or down to avoid the side buttons.

Update (15 Jun 2015)
Added an OpenSCAD version that can be customized to your phone and bike. There are also a couple minor changes to reduce obstruction to the screen and home button.

This was inspired by Biel's design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:176132), but is not a remix. Compared to the other phone holder designs on Thingiverse, this one is meant to be ultra light (8 grams) and easy to print (zero bridges or overhangs, and prints in well under an hour), while still holding the phone pretty firmly (...yet to test this fully, but I'll update on the result the next time I hit a bus). You'll need a couple of zip ties to secure this to your bike.

Designed in FreeCAD (fcstd file is included) (OpenSCAD version added) and printed in ABS using Cura. Should work just fine with PETG and PLA.
It is strongly recommended to use the customizer version (...click "Open in Customizer"), but the original STL files are still available for those who wants them. The following instructions are for the older STL version:
The STL file contains 2 parts, and you'll have to split them up and lay them flat before printing (...in Slic3r, right click and select "Split".).  
It should not be hard modifying this to fit your phone model using FreeCAD, but be warned that FreeCAD (...at least for the version 0.14 that I'm using) seems to have trouble making up its mind and may complain about redundant constraints when the dimensions are changed.

description.text:
I designed this to install a laser diode module on a rigidbot extruder carriage. I specifically have a 2.8W 445nm module from jtechphotonics.com, so that's what the measurements were based on. You can attach the laser module with either zip ties or two M3x7mm (or longer) machine screws with M3 nuts. This installs onto the printer using the two x carriage cap screws that would normally hold your part cooling fan in place. You should be able to use the original screws. The mount was designed/tested on a single extruder Rigidbot Big. it should also work on the smaller model, and MIGHT work with the dual extruder setup. I consider this to be a version 1.0. It works, but I would like more flexibility to keep a part cooling fan mounted and/or a laser-cooling/smoke blowing fan. I added a photo of my first successful laser cut out of an aborted PLA print. You can also see to the left of the piece the difference between focused and unfocused accuracy of the laser - thin vs thick lines. In the background I'm printing an ornament based on this design.

comments.text: How has the laser worked on the RigidBot? Is there any difficult tasks when hooking it all together and what do you use to produce the gcode for it?
comments.author: ibraud

comments.text:
I wound up soldering some longer cables for the laser and control line (connects to part cooling fan output on extruder board) to run wiring out to the laser driver board. The quality of the lasered items was much, MUCH better using PWM than when using CW/constant on, so that's worth it. I used inkscape with the plugin provided on jtech's website to make gcode. I did have to figure out a safe starting position for the laser since it's possible to cut through the RB's Y belt if you're not careful. You also need to focus the laser - I moved the Z axis up about 30mm and test fired pulses at the painters tape on the bed along the x axis, making small adjustments to get the burned dot as small as possible. From there I can measure the thickness of an object I'm lasering and offset the y axis by 30mm + the height of the work piece. I usually do a dry run of the gcode on the printer with the laser driver powered off if i'm not sure about position or something. I quickly discovered that I don't enjoy breathing or smelling smoke from wood or leather and OMFG, never laze ABS plastic - it out-gasses cyanide when it burns. So I built a full enclosure using 3 of the jtech orange acrylic panels and some corrugated plastic sheet from Home Depot. Sealed up the cracks with kapton tape. Added a fan and duct adapter for some dryer hose to send the fumes out a nearby window. As a final touch, I bought and mounted enclosure switch for the laser board so that the laser shuts off if the front acrylic panel is removed. Some of the parts I used and/or designed:

title: Iphone 5S dock replacement shell V2 - for Iphone 5S including case

description.text:
Updated: (Version 2 changes detailed at the bottom) This replaces the original Apple shell for an Iphone 5S docking stand and allows the use of an Iphone with a case. It uses the original base, electronics and weight. Because of the differences in Iphone cases, different spacers may need to be installed in the bottom of the phone slot. I've also included the model for the base spacer used for the current case we're using. Version 2
The second version of this base is modified to increase the side wall height to hold the phone more snugly. The first version let the phone wiggle from side to side which would occasionally cancel charging. The black strips seen in the picture are pieces of tape that can be added and subtracted as needed to fit different cases. There are a few other minor tweaks that make the case fit the Apple dock easier. I haven't needed the stand spacer with version 2 but I am leaving the file available in case it helps with a different case.

To disassemble your apple dock, remove the bottom rubber pad.  It is stuck on with adhesive.  The less you bend this rubber pad the better it will reinstall later, if you have a spudger or similar tool, use it.  
Next the 6 tabs on the dock top need to be pried away from the dock bottom.  Finally, the dock bottom and top need to be separated.  There is adhesive securing the bottom and top and gentle prying will eventually separate these pieces.  
Next the dock bottom can be snapped into place in the newly printed dock top.
